Introduction

The dataset I will be working with comes from the World Bank website. The goal of this project is to use different clustering algorithms to find subgroups/clusters in the World Development Indicator dataset. Clustering is a type of unsupervised learning to divide the dataset into multiple groups where observations that are more similar are placed in the same cluster. Unlike the supervised learning models we have been learning in this course where we have already assigned identity/responses (i.e.they are already in groups) to each observation, clustering is simply trying to use the variables in our observations to group them into separate responses based on the similarity of these observations.

In my dataset, the different countries are the observations, and the development indicators (access to electricity, population, mortality rate etc.) are the variables.

Unsupervised learning is very important for data scientists because it allows you to find patterns in data that made no sense beforehand. There are a lot of clustering algorithms out there. In this project, I will use the kmeans clustering method and hierarchical clustering method.

The chart above illustrates the number of variables whose max is in each buckets on a scale from zero to the trillions. On the left, its probably the variables like percentages, rates. In the middle, its the variables like arable land, population, and mobile cellular subscriptions that are on the millions scale, and also variables like foreign direct investments and merchandise exports that are on the billions scale. On the right, its the variables like GDP which is on the trillions scale.

As we can see, the different indicators have different scales. The value for GDP is much larger than that for percentages (there are a lot of indicators in the form of percentages).

While some clustering algorithms can be used for categorical variables, kmeans and hierarchical clustering are mostly used for numerical variables. Both algorithms use distances between observations to measure dissimilarity, so if our variables are on different scales, the variable on a larger scale will tend to have bigger differences, and thus will be the driver for the dissimilarity between observations. In this case, I would like to let all the variables have equal weight because they are not comparable with each other, so I will scale my variables.

world_2014_copy <- world_2014
world_2014_copy$country <-NULL
world_2014_matrix <- data.matrix(world_2014_copy)
world_2014_matrix <- scale(world_2014_matrix)

Clustering

Now we have a clean matrix to apply our clustering algorithms!

K-means Algorithm

K-means is the most basic and most commonly used clustering algorithm. It works as following:

  1. pick random centroids to start with.

  2. assign each observation to the different centroids by computing the euclidean distances between the centroid and all of the observations, the goal is to assign each observation to the closest centroid.

  3. for the resulting clusters, compute the centroid within each cluster so that the sum of the distances between all the oberservations to the centroid is minimized.

  4. repeat 2 and 3 until the assignments no longer change.

Heres a visual way of understanding the algorithm from http://sherrytowers.com/2013/10/24/k-means-clustering/

To use the kmeans algorithm, the first step is to determine the optimal number of centroids. There are multiple methods that can help determine the optimal number of centroids.

1.pamk function:

library(fpc)
clusters <- pamk(world_2014_matrix)
n <- clusters$nc
n
## [1] 2

2.elbow method:

The idea here is that the within-cluster variance will continue to decrease as the number of cluster increases. However, the extent of such decrease in variance will begin to be not so significant at some number of cluster, and this point will be the optimal number of clusters because increasing the number of clusters will not effectively decrease the within-cluster variance anymore.

wss<- (nrow(world_2014_matrix)-1)*sum(apply(world_2014_matrix,2,var))

for (i in 2:25) wss[i] <- sum(kmeans(world_2014_matrix, 
centers=i, nstart = 20)$withinss)
plot(1:25, wss, type="b", xlab="Number of clusters",
ylab="Within groups sum of squares")

dev.copy(png,filename="elbowMethod.png", width=600, height=875);
## quartz_off_screen 
##                 3
dev.off ();
## quartz_off_screen 
##                 2

The preceding code is taken from Tal Galilis post based on Chapter 16, R in Action, Second Edition, By Rob Kabacoff.

So these two methods drew different conclusions about how many clusters are optimal. famk method stated 2 clusters, while elbow method stated 4 clusters. I will then look at the results using 2 and 4 clusters.

So now we have divided our observations (countries) into 2 subgroups, we can use these subgroups as the response, and fit a supervised model to it. I will use the glmnet model to find which variables correlate to which cluster. The code below will help me understand what variables had the most weight in determining the assignment of clusters.

Connectivity-based (Hierarchical) clustering

Remember that using the k-means algorithm requires an input of the number of clusters, but this can be difficult if you have no idea how many clusters you should have. Hierarchical clustering, on the other hand, does not require an initial input on the number of clusters. Instead, it maps out the entire process of forming clusters, or dividing up clusters. Hierarchical clustering can be divided into two approaches:

Agglomerative vs.Divisive

Agglomerative: the process of fusing the n observations into groups, eventually end up with 1 final group containing all n observations.

Divisive: the process of breaking down the n observations into groups, eventually end up with n final groups each containing 1 observation.

Both approaches will allow us to see what the optimal division of groups. In the end, we can observe the entire fusing/dividing process through a dendrogram, which illustrates the entire clustering process.

Just like k-means, the similarity between observations is measured through the distances. However, while k-means uses euclidean distances only, hierarchical learning allows the choices of different methods for distance calculation.For binary data, there are Jaccard coefficient, Rogers and Tanimoto, Sneath and Sokal, and Gower and Legendre. For multivariable continuous data, there are Euclidean, Manhattan, Minkowski, Pearson correlation, and Angular separation. For this project, I will use the most commonly used Euclidean distance.

This article has a great table for the comparison of different distance http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article/file?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0144059&type=printable

What is hierarchical clustering?

The agglomerative approach is similar but opposite from the divisive approach. Agglomerative hierarchical clustering is the most commonly adapted algorithm, so I will describe the process as following:

  1. Start with each observation as their own group
  2. measure the distances between each observation, and notice that there can be different ways of calculating the distances. Then, you can choose different methods to follow in order to decide which two observations to fuse together. The methods are:
  • single linkage: this will result in the fusion of the closest two observations/groups
  • complete linkage: this will result in the fusion of the furthest two observations/groups
  • average linkage: this will fuse the observations/groups with the smallest average distance between all pairs of observations from each group
  • centroid linkage: this will fuse the groups with the smallest distance between the centroids of each group
  • Wards method: this will fuse based on the increase in sum of squares for all variables within clusters after fusion
  1. The fusion will continue to take place until all of the observations have been fused into one group, which contains all of the observations.

The process above will be recorded and demonstrated through the dendrogram, where the fusions at each stage are shown, and the height of each fusion represents the distance upon such fusion.

Below, I will illustrate how the dendrograms differ for each of the linkage methods. All of the distances are measured as euclidean distances.

Complete Linkage

set.seed(1)
distmeasure<- dist(world_2014_matrix, method = "euclidean")
